# LinkedIn Article Writing Rules

These rules guide the creation of LinkedIn articles that position the author as a technical frontend developer with leadership aspirations, who is always available to help, teach, and learn.

## Writing Style

### Tone and Voice

- **Technical but friendly and humorous**: Use technical terminology accurately but explain concepts in an approachable way with subtle humor
- **First person singular ALWAYS**: Write in first person singular ("implementé", "organicé", "usé", "me ahorró") - the library was built solo, not by a team
- **Witty and entertaining**: Add light humor, parenthetical comments, and technical jokes to make reading enjoyable while maintaining technical accuracy
- **Authentic and personal**: Admit mistakes, share real struggles, include personal anecdotes about the development process
- **Helpful and available**: Always convey willingness to help others and answer questions
- **Teaching mindset**: Share knowledge generously, explain the "why" behind decisions
- **Learning attitude**: Show openness to learning new technologies and approaches
- **Leadership positioning**: Demonstrate technical depth while showing ability to guide and mentor

### Language

- Write in Spanish (as per user preference)
- Use clear, concise sentences
- Avoid overly complex jargon unless necessary
- Include code examples when relevant
- **NEVER use emojis** - No emojis under any circumstances
- **Use first person singular**: Always use "yo", "mí", "me", "mi" - never "nosotros", "nuestro", "implementamos"
- **Add humor naturally**: Include witty comments in parentheses, technical jokes, and light observations that make reading enjoyable
- **Be authentic**: Admit when things were hard, when mistakes were made, when solutions came after trial and error

## Article Structure

### Title

- Should be clear and descriptive
- Can be technical but accessible
- Example: "Creando un Design System desde cero"

### Introduction

- Hook the reader with a relatable problem or question
- Share personal context or motivation
- Set expectations for what the article will cover

### Body

- Break content into clear sections with headers
- Use bullet points or numbered lists for clarity
- Include code examples with explanations
- Share both successes and challenges
- Reference external resources (documentation, GitHub, etc.)

### Conclusion

- Summarize key takeaways
- Invite discussion and questions
- Offer to help or share more resources
- Include call-to-action (CTAs) for engagement

## Content Guidelines

### Technical Content

- Explain concepts from first principles when helpful
- Show implementation details without overwhelming
- Reference actual code and documentation
- Include links to relevant resources
- Share architectural decisions and rationale

### Personal Touch

- **Always use first person singular**: "Implementé", "organicé", "usé", "me ahorró", "mi código", "mis tokens" - never plural forms
- Share learning journey and challenges with honesty and humor
- Mention what you're still learning
- Acknowledge mistakes and how you learned from them (with a touch of humor)
- Show enthusiasm for the technology
- Write authentically, as you would speak about technical topics to a colleague
- Include specific technical details and real decisions made
- Avoid generic or formulaic expressions
- **Add personality**: Include witty parenthetical comments, technical jokes, and observations that make the article entertaining
- **Examples of humor style**:
  - "Sí, chartreuse. Porque ¿por qué no?"
  - "Porque 8 es un número bonito y divisible"
  - "TypeScript es mi mejor amigo y mi peor enemigo"
  - "porque Redux me daba pesadillas"
  - "Rebelde, lo sé"
  - "Control total = menos bugs = más tiempo para café"
  - "casi lloro de felicidad" (when something worked well)
  - "Spoiler: no lo fue" (when something was harder than expected)

### Engagement

- Ask questions to readers
- Invite comments and discussion
- Offer to help with specific questions
- Share resources and documentation links

## Formatting

### Text Formatting

- Use **bold** for emphasis on key concepts
- Use _italics_ sparingly for emphasis
- Use code formatting for technical terms: `ThemeProvider`
- Use line breaks for readability

### Code Examples

- Keep code snippets concise and relevant
- Add comments to explain complex parts
- Reference full documentation for complete examples
- Use language tags when possible

### Links

- Always include links to relevant documentation
- Link to GitHub repositories when appropriate
- Reference official documentation sites
- Use descriptive link text

